# PURPOSE
# -------
# Visual test for the coordinate math used by {WCLICK} tokens in
# kwin_restore.py input_actions injection.
#
# Shows a 1000×1000 window with a dot grid every 25 px.  When the user
# clicks anywhere inside the window:
#   - A 48 px red filled circle with white crosshair is drawn at the
#     click position and fades out after 1 second.
#   - The title bar updates to show both window-relative and absolute
#     compositor coordinates of the click.
#
# This directly simulates what kwin_restore.py does for {WCLICK x, y}:
#
#     abs_x = window_x + x
#     abs_y = window_y + y
#     NotifyPointerMotionAbsolute(abs_x, abs_y)
#
# Qt's mapToGlobal() returns the same absolute compositor coordinate.
# If the dot appears exactly where you clicked, the math is correct and
# {WCLICK} tokens will land where they should during a restore.
#
# No child process or ClickIndicator is used — all painting is done
# directly on the canvas to avoid Wayland input-blocking issues.
#
# USAGE
# -----
#   python3 docs/dev/kwin_click.py
#
# REQUIREMENTS
#   PyQt6   (sudo zypper install python313-qt6)
